n it should. I had a limit of 4MB, but the<br />&gt; size went up to 12MB (5MB resident).<br /><br />Umm, _what_ size? If you set a RLIMIT_DATA (or whatever the name is), <br />that will only make a difference for the process bss (*), and if grep <br />uses mmap(), then we'd need to have a "virtual memory" limit. However, we <br />don't have any such limit, although I added a RLIMIT_AS for 2.0 (but it's <br />currently unchecked).<br /><br />(*) that's the curent Linux interpretation, at least. Do other unixes <br />consider mmap'ed data part of RLIMIT_DATA?<br /><br />&gt;	 			Also I was able to run the memtest<br />&gt; program on 8MB despite datasize limited to 1MB. Hmm I have to check the<br />&gt; sources to see what happened. And my program with a global definition of<br />&gt; 'char a[128MB]' still dumpos core.<br /><br />Well, dumping core is the corect thing to do - it failed to get the BSS <br />at exec time, so when the program actually ran it was "kind of" unhappy..<br /><br />		Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
